# OPA/Rego Policy Baseline

Companion project to [`semantic-agent-policy-mvp`](../semantic-agent-policy-mvp/).
Runs the **same five agent-action scenarios** using [OPA](https://www.openpolicyagent.org/)
Rego policies (evaluated in-process via [regopy](https://pypi.org/project/regopy/)),
so you can compare the two approaches side-by-side.

---

## Quick start

```bash
cd opa-policy-baseline

python -m venv .venv
# Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate
source .venv/bin/activate

pip install -r requirements.txt
python run_validation.py --all
```

Expected output:

```
Scenario : restart_denied
Decision : REQUIRE_APPROVAL

Scenario : restart_allowed
Decision : ALLOW

Scenario : restart_staging_allowed
Decision : ALLOW

Scenario : skill_preload_review
Decision : REQUIRE_APPROVAL

Scenario : skill_postload_denied
Decision : DENY
```

---

## The core comparison

| Concept | Semantic baseline (RDF/OWL/SHACL) | This baseline (OPA/Rego) |
|---|---|---|
| Production-ness | Encoded **once** as ontology equivalentClass rule; OWL **infers** `srv_123 a ProductionServer` from `belongsToEnvironment :production` | **Manually** listed in `production_servers := {"srv_123"}` |
| Staging-ness | OWL infers `srv_456 a StagingServer` | Manually listed in `staging_servers` |
| Unverified skill | OWL infers `a UnverifiedSkill` from `hasVerificationStatus :Unverified` | Manually listed in `unverified_finance_skills` |
| Finance-write check | SHACL queries `?tool :requiresPermission :FinanceWriteAccess` separately | Collapsed into same hand-maintained set |
| Adding a new prod server | Add one triple: `:srv_999 :belongsToEnvironment :production` | Add to `production_servers` set **and** any other affected sets |
| Reusability | OWL class hierarchy is globally reusable across shapes | Rego sets must be re-enumerated per policy package |

### Why this matters

In the semantic baseline, production-ness is an **ontological property**:

```turtle
# data/enterprise.ttl — one fact
:srv_123 :belongsToEnvironment :production .

# data/ontology.ttl — one reusable rule
:ProductionServer owl:equivalentClass [
    owl:intersectionOf (:Server
        [owl:onProperty :belongsToEnvironment ;
         owl:hasValue   :production]) ] .
```

OWL inference **materialises** `:srv_123 a :ProductionServer` at runtime.
The SHACL shape then simply asks `?server a :ProductionServer` — no hardcoded IDs anywhere.

In this Rego baseline the same fact is encoded manually:

```rego
# policies/agent_policy.rego — manual list, must be kept in sync
production_servers := {"srv_123"}
```

The Rego rule works correctly, but any new production server must be added
to this set by a human.  The ontology approach propagates automatically.

